name: Test -> Control‑to‑Load series path (including the switch path and any series elements before the load input),
description: With power applied and the switch closed, measure voltage at the control module output terminals (the pair feeding the load). First, measure across the two output conductors to confirm the control module is actually delivering ~12 V when the switch is ON. Then, keeping the negative probe on the system 0 V reference, move the positive probe stepwise: control‑module output terminal, corresponding connector at the load input, and finally the anode side of the load’s series diode. Identify the exact point along this path where the voltage drops from ~12 V down to ~0.36 V to locate an internal open/high‑resistance fault or unintended series element between the control output and the load input cable (+)., outcome='Control module output and load input both show ~0.36 V on the (+) conductors relative to 0 V, with 0 V on all (−) conductors. The same ~0.36 V appears at the anode of the load’s series diode, with 0 V at its cathode, so the drop from expected ~12 V to ~0.36 V is already present at the control module output (+) and persists unchanged up to the diode anode.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=110.0, cost_breakdown=[('close_switch', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> Power supply output and control‑module input (under load and no‑load),
description: With the switch open (lamp disconnected), measure the voltage between the PSU output (+) and (−); then measure between the control‑module input pair on the PSU side. Close the switch and repeat the same measurements. Compare: if the PSU output stays near 12 V with switch open but collapses to ~0.36 V with switch closed while the green LED remains lit, the PSU module has excessive internal series resistance or current‑limit fault. If the PSU output is already only ~0.36 V even with the switch open, the PSU cannot provide 12 V at all and is faulty. If the PSU remains at ~12 V in both cases but the control‑module input shows ~0.36 V only when the switch is closed, then there is an abnormal series resistance or partial open between the PSU terminals and the control‑module input connectors., outcome='With the switch open, the PSU Output Cable (+) is at ~11.99 V and PSU Output Cable (−) is at 0 V; the Control Input Cable (+) and (−) show the same respective voltages. With the switch closed, all these voltages remain unchanged (~11.99 V on (+), 0 V on (−)) at both the PSU output and the control‑module input. No polarity inversion is indicated by the measured voltages.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=180.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_switch', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('close_switch', 10.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
